<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Henry, Alexander. Travels in the Red River Department (Abridged), 1806. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0024</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">4</span>
</p>
<p><span class="fw">1806</span>
</p>
<p>July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">deep vallies covered with stunted trees of Pine, Birch, and poplar<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The soil is poor dry and san<span class="AddHand-editors">[dy]</span><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  At Two Came to the Devils Mountain which we could see from a great distance &#8212; and is composed of sand, several miles in circumference<span class="AddHand-editors">[,]</span> flat upon the Top without the least sign of Vegetation.  Our road lay along the foot of this high mountain over heavy sand into which our Horses Sunk up to the knees<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  There are many curious stories told of this Extraordinary elevation. Soon after we came to Riviere a la Sourie.  The Hudson Bay Establishment is on the north side the men of which we found busily employed making hair lines for their horses.  These are very neat and formed generally of the hair which the Buffaloes have between their horns<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Those made of horse hair are stronger.  The Hudson Bay men ferryed us over to our own Fort where we found M<sup>r</sup> Chaboillez and M<sup>r</sup> Allen M<sup>c</sup>Donnell of Fort Dauphin on their way to swan River<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  They were four Days on their way having crossed the Fort Dauphin Mountains<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  M<sup>r</sup> LaRoc has the post in charge<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  No trade of any kind at this place<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The Indians have been absent for a month and a half which causes a great scarcity of provissions<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Sunday 13 </p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Found myself still unwell &#8212; but made preparations for my Journey<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[M]</span>any obstacles were thrown in my Way to prevent my undertaking it but I was determined<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  M<sup>r</sup> Allen M<sup>c</sup>Donnell and a Young Sauteur consented to join us, and now I found matters went on more smoothly.  Our guide is an</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">Irishman-</p>

